TY  - JOUR
AU  - Biais, Bruno
AU  - Bisière, Christophe
AU  - Bouvard, Matthieu
AU  - Casamatta, Catherine
T1  - The Blockchain Folk Theorem
PY  - 2019
Y1  - 2019/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhy095
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 32
IS  - 5
SP  - 1662
EP  - 1715
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Blockchains are distributed ledgers, operated within peer-to-peer networks. We model the proof-of-work blockchain protocol as a stochastic game and analyze the equilibrium strategies of rational, strategic miners. Mining the longest chain is a Markov perfect equilibrium, without forking, in line with Nakamoto (2008). The blockchain protocol, however, is a coordination game, with multiple equilibria. There exist equilibria with forks, leading to orphaned blocks and persistent divergence between chains. We also show how forks can be generated by information delays and software upgrades. Last we identify negative externalities implying that equilibrium investment in computing capacity is excessive.Received May 31, 2017; editorial decision July 6, 2018 by Editor Itay Goldstein.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhy095
ER  - 



