TY  - JOUR
AU  - D’Acunto, Francesco
AU  - Prabhala, Nagpurnanand
AU  - Rossi, Alberto G
T1  - The Promises and Pitfalls of Robo-Advising
PY  - 2019
Y1  - 2019/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhz014
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 32
IS  - 5
SP  - 1983
EP  - 2020
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We study the introduction of a wealth-management robo-adviser that constructs portfolios tailored to investors’ holdings and preferences. Adopters are similar to non-adopters in terms of demographics and prior interactions with human advisers but tend to be more active and have greater assets under management. Investors adopting robo-advising experience diversification benefits. Ex ante undiversified investors increase stock holdings and hold portfolios with less volatility and better returns. Already well-diversified investors hold fewer stocks, yet see some reduction in volatility, and trade more after adoption. All investors increase attention based on online account logins. We find that adopters exhibit declines in prominent behavioral biases, including the disposition, trend chasing, and rank effect. Our results emphasize the promises and pitfalls of robo-advising tools, which are becoming ubiquitous all over the world.Received May 31, 2017; editorial decision August 21, 2018 by Editor Wei Jiang.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhz014
ER  - 



